  '1dd57e2b-f61b-426f-9101-53e8a2635a0d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Playwright Testing Pyramid — What to Test at Each Layer$escape$,
  $escape$Playwright operates at the E2E layer, but that doesn't mean every test should be E2E. Structure tests in three tiers.

**Unit (skip Playwright):** Pure logic — date formatters, validators, state reducers. Use Vitest or Jest. Playwright adds zero value here and only slows CI.

**Component/Integration (use Playwright CT):** `@playwright/experimental-ct-react` lets you mount isolated components inside a real browser. Test a `<DatePicker />` keyboard navigation, ARIA roles, and focus trapping without a full app. Faster than full E2E, catches browser-specific DOM quirks that jsdom misses.

**E2E (full Playwright):** Reserve for critical user journeys — auth flows, checkout, form submissions with network calls. Use `page.route()` to stub flaky third-party APIs, keeping tests deterministic. Rely on `locator()` with ARIA roles (`getByRole('button', { name: 'Submit' })`) over CSS selectors to mirror how users and screen readers perceive the UI.

A healthy ratio: ~70% unit, ~20% component, ~10% E2E. Playwright CT is the underused middle layer most teams skip entirely.$escape$,
  $escape$// Component test with Playwright CT — isolated, real browser
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/experimental-ct-react';
import { DatePicker } from './DatePicker';

test('closes on Escape and returns focus to trigger', async ({ mount }) => {
  const component = await mount(<DatePicker label="Due date" />);

  await component.getByRole('button', { name: 'Due date' }).click();
  await expect(component.getByRole('dialog')).toBeVisible();

  await component.press('Escape');
  await expect(component.getByRole('dialog')).toBeHidden();
  await expect(component.getByRole('button', { name: 'Due date' })).toBeFocused();
});$escape$,
