INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ede42f2d-920b-48fb-91a6-aeed4796bbf7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Playwright API Mocking — MSW Handlers vs page.route() and When Real Deps Win$escape$,
  $escape$Playwright ships two mocking primitives: `page.route()` for test-local interception and `route.fulfill()` to return fixtures inline. These are fine for one-offs, but they don't share handlers with your unit tests. That's where `playwright-msw` earns its place — it mounts real MSW service workers inside the Playwright browser context, so the same handler definitions used in Vitest or Jest run verbatim in E2E. This eliminates drift between mock layers.

Use mocks when: third-party APIs have rate limits, you're testing loading/error UI states that are hard to reproduce reliably, or you need deterministic latency with `worker.use(http.get(..., { delay: 200 }))`. Use real dependencies when: you're verifying a write path end-to-end (auth token exchange, database mutation with RLS, payment webhook), or when the mock would underspecify the integration contract. Mock the edges you don't own; test the system you do. In Playwright specifically, `page.route()` can intercept even service-worker-forwarded requests, so it remains your escape hatch when MSW handler order matters.$escape$,
  $escape$// playwright/fixtures.ts — reuse MSW handlers in Playwright
import { createWorkerFixture } from 'playwright-msw';
import { http, HttpResponse } from 'msw';
import { handlers } from '../src/mocks/handlers'; // shared with Vitest

const worker = await createWorkerFixture(handlers);

// Override a single handler inside a test
await worker.use(
  http.get('/api/bytes', () =>
    HttpResponse.json({ data: [], nextCursor: null })
  )
);

// Force an error state
await worker.use(
  http.post('/api/bytes', () => new HttpResponse(null, { status: 503 }))
);$escape$,
