INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a7a8716c-f509-4dcc-b9fc-50b0dac119a7',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Playwright Snapshot Testing — When It Helps vs When It Becomes Noise$escape$,
  $escape$Playwright offers two snapshot flavors: `toMatchSnapshot()` for pixel-level screenshots and `toHaveScreenshot()` (the modern, preferred API) for visual regression with built-in retry and threshold options. They shine for catching unintended UI regressions in stable, deterministic components — charts, design system primitives, marketing pages. The failure signal is high when the component has no dynamic content.

The noise starts when you snapshot components with timestamps, user avatars, animated elements, or data from live APIs. Every CI run produces a diff, but none of it is a real regression. The fix isn't to widen `maxDiffPixels` blindly — it's to mask dynamic regions with `page.locator('.timestamp').evaluate(el => el.textContent = '...')` before snapshotting, or to use `clip` to isolate only the stable portion of the viewport.

Update snapshots intentionally with `--update-snapshots`, never as a reflex. Treat a snapshot update the same as a schema migration: review it in the PR diff. Store `.png` baselines in version control but keep them co-located with the test file via the `snapshotDir` config to avoid orphaned files accumulating silently.$escape$,
  $escape$import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('pricing card visual regression', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('/pricing');

  // Mask dynamic badge (e.g. 'Popular' with live user count)
  await page.locator('[data-testid="user-count"]').evaluate(
    el => (el.textContent = '10k users')
  );

  await expect(page.locator('[data-testid="pricing-card"]')).toHaveScreenshot(
    'pricing-card.png',
    { maxDiffPixels: 5, animations: 'disabled' }
  );
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
