INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a9a31c20-2219-4e16-ac1b-6d36deb5e50a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Playwright CI Integration — Parallelizing Tests, Caching, and Fail-Fast Strategies$escape$,
  $escape$Playwright's built-in sharding splits your test suite across CI workers without any external orchestration. Set `--shard=1/4` through `--shard=4/4` across four parallel jobs, then merge results with `npx playwright merge-reports`. Each shard runs a distinct subset of spec files, cutting wall-clock time linearly.

Cache the `.playwright-browsers` directory (resolved via `npx playwright install --dry-run`) keyed on the Playwright version in `package-lock.json`. Browser binaries rarely change — skipping re-downloads saves 30–90 seconds per run.

For fail-fast behavior, Playwright doesn't expose a native `--bail` flag, but `maxFailures` in `playwright.config.ts` stops the run after N failures across all workers. Set `maxFailures: 1` in CI to abort immediately on the first flake, preventing wasted worker minutes. Combine with `retries: 0` in CI (non-zero retries mask flakiness) and `reporter: [['github'], ['blob']]` so GitHub Actions annotates failing lines directly. Use the `blob` reporter per shard, then `merge-reports` to produce a unified HTML report as a CI artifact.$escape$,
  $escape$// playwright.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  workers: process.env.CI ? 4 : undefined,
  retries: process.env.CI ? 0 : 1,
  maxFailures: process.env.CI ? 1 : 0,
  reporter: process.env.CI
    ? [['github'], ['blob', { outputDir: 'blob-report' }]]
    : [['html']],
  use: {
    trace: 'retain-on-failure',
  },
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
